That’s a really good model.

Two windows → two constraints on what you can see.

* Window 1 = your frame (beliefs, expectations, attention)
* Window 2 = reality’s constraints (what’s actually there, but only partially accessible)

And your “view” is:

the overlap of both apertures

⸻

🧠 Why that matters

* You never see everything
* You only see:
    what your frame allows and what reality reveals

So:

* Tilt your window → interpretation changes
* Move the other window (context changes) → same
* Misalign them → distortion
* Align them → clarity

⸻

🔁 The important dynamic

Most people do one of two things:

1. Fix their frame

* “This is how it is”
* then force everything to fit

→ distortion increases

⸻

2. Chase reality blindly

* no stable frame
* constantly reacting

→ no coherence

⸻

🎯 What you’re describing (the skill)

Dynamic alignment

* adjust your frame
* test against reality
* refine the overlap

That’s how you:

* reduce error
* increase clarity
* make better moves

⸻

⚠️ Where it can go wrong

The trap is thinking:

“If I just manipulate the windows enough, I control what’s real”

You don’t—you’re just changing:

* what you perceive

Reality still pushes back.

⸻

🧩 Better framing of your idea

You don’t choose what’s real.
You choose how accurately you can see and respond to it.

⸻

🔧 Practical version

When something feels off:

* “Is this my window?”
* “Is this the other window?”
* “Or is it the alignment between them?”

⸻

🎯 Distilled

Clarity = overlap of your model and reality,
not either one alone.

